data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt`** — so no abort-related migration is needed.

The APIs you do use — `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — work identically in .NET 8.

That said, this code would benefit from modernization to `Task`-based parallelism:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item)));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This gives you built-in support for `CancellationToken` if you need cancellation later — the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort`.
